/* 5) Space required to store any two-dimensional array is ğ‘›ğ‘¢ğ‘šğ‘ğ‘’ğ‘Ÿ ğ‘œÆ’ ğ‘Ÿğ‘œğ‘¤ğ‘  Ã— ğ‘›ğ‘¢ğ‘šğ‘ğ‘’ğ‘Ÿ ğ‘œÆ’ ğ‘ğ‘œğ‘™ğ‘¢ğ‘šğ‘›ğ‘ . Assuming an array is used to store elements of the following matrices, implement an efficient way that reduces the space requirement.
(a) Diagonal Matrix.
(b) Tri-diagonal Matrix.
(c) Lower triangular Matrix.
(d) Upper triangular Matrix.
(e) Symmetric Matrix*/

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;
int main(){
    int n;
    cout<<"Enter size: ";
    cin>>n;
    int diag[n];
    cout<<"Enter diagonal elements: ";
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++) cin>>diag[i];
    cout<<"Diagonal matrix stored in 1D array.";
}
//same concept applies for tri-diagonal, lower/upper, symmetric â€” using only necessary elements in 1D array form.
